PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255336
DO  - 10.5465/255336
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 340
EP  - 343
VL  - 16
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article describes some characteristics of the firm, employees and community that influence union organizations in the U.S. According to the author, there are characteristics of the particular firm, community, and employees which greatly influence union election results, including age, race, sex, length of service and education. The author says these are some of the major factors that affect an employee?s decision to vote for a union. He also states that an employee?s need for acceptance is related to the size, previous experience with the union, and other characteristics of the community. The author believes there is less chance of having an employee vote for a union in a smaller community without previous experience with collective bargaining.
AB  - The article describes some characteristics of the firm, employees and community that influence union organizations in the U.S. According to the author, there are characteristics of the particular firm, community, and employees which greatly influence union election results, including age, race, sex, length of service and education. The author says these are some of the major factors that affect an employee?s decision to vote for a union. He also states that an employee?s need for acceptance is related to the size, previous experience with the union, and other characteristics of the community. The author believes there is less chance of having an employee vote for a union in a smaller community without previous experience with collective bargaining.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255336
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255336
